<article class="border-l-4 border-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] pl-6">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-1">July 7, 2026</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-4">Shipped <code>/compare/breederbuddy-alternative</code> as page C2 of the 12-page LP cluster plan (<code>docs/marketing/LP-CLUSTER-PLAN-2026-06.md</code>). Second of five conquesting-Ads-targeted comparison pages, alongside the already-live <code>/compare/breedercloudpro-alternative</code> (C1).</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
    <p>
      <strong>Why.</strong> The strategy doc&apos;s conquesting Ads campaign bids on <em>[competitor] alternative</em> queries; <em>breederbuddy alternative</em> is one of the five named targets. The page&apos;s job is to capture that intent honestly and convert qualified searchers to <code>/pricing</code> or the trial, without misrepresenting BreederBuddy or the BreederHQ trust posture.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>What the page is.</strong> An editorial honest-comparison page modeled on the C1 BreederCloudPro precedent. H1: <em>Looking for a BreederBuddy Alternative? An Honest Comparison</em>. Eight-section structure per the brief: hero with dual CTA + "Last verified" date, TL;DR (when each is the right pick), publicly-verifiable comparison table (entry price, trial, species, marketplace, buyer portal, OFA Sync, mobile), a mandatory "where BreederBuddy is genuinely strong" section with three concrete strengths, six capability differences for BreederHQ, dual pricing detail cards, an honest-scope footer that links to <code>/trust</code>, and a final CTA repeating the trial and FOUNDER50 framing.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Verified claims.</strong> Pre-publish probe against breederbuddy.com on 2026-07-07 confirmed the three load-bearing claims from the brief: $29.99/mo (and $300/year), 30-day free trial with no credit card required, and one species per account (dog OR cat, switchable in Settings). The optional website add-on at +$29.99/mo is described accurately as a private storefront rather than a public marketplace. Every claim about BreederBuddy on the page is sourced to its public site; no private trial findings, no screenshots, no inferred customer counts.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Anti-cannibalization.</strong> H1 uses "alternative" instead of "best ... software" — keeps the page out of the <code>/compare/best-dog-breeding-software</code> head-term lane. The deeper buyer&apos;s guide handoff is a single link out to <code>/compare/best-dog-breeding-software</code> rather than a duplicated comparison matrix. No "best of" framing, no star ratings or scores (matches the existing <code>/compare</code> voice and FAQ Q18 on the dog page).
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Schema.</strong> One JSON-LD block — editorial <code>Article</code> with author/publisher/image/datePublished/dateModified/mainEntityOfPage. Deliberately NOT <code>SoftwareApplication</code> on this page: the page is editorial, BaseLayout already emits a global product block for BreederHQ, and a second product block here would misrepresent the page as a BreederHQ vendor page rather than a comparison. <code>FAQPage</code> and <code>BreadcrumbList</code> auto-emit through BaseLayout props.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Outbound links from the new page</strong> satisfy the per-page contract from the brief: <code>/pricing</code> (primary, repeated), <code>/compare/best-dog-breeding-software</code> (deeper buyer&apos;s guide), <code>/breeder-management-software</code> (Cluster A1 sibling for species-neutral overview), <code>/trust</code> (honesty posture), and <code>/</code> via the breadcrumb. External outbound to breederbuddy.com&apos;s pricing page uses <code>rel="nofollow noopener"</code>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Honesty constraints honored.</strong> Trial language is "14-day free trial" — never "free tier," never "no time limit." FOUNDER50 framed as "first 100 founders" for 50% off Pro or Enterprise for 12 months. Trust posture is reproduced verbatim from the locked language: we do NOT verify, vet, or vouch; only Stripe Identity passthrough, public-registry passthrough, and provider self-attestation. No "tenant" / "tenant-wide" anywhere in user-facing copy — uses "operation," "account," and "program." No fake stats, no star ratings, no implied controlled-test scoring.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Disclaimer footer.</strong> Closing block makes explicit that BreederHQ is not affiliated with, endorsed by, or sponsored by BreederBuddy, and that BreederBuddy is referenced only to describe the same category of software so buyers can compare options. Matches the disclaimer pattern on the existing Sniffspot-alternative and BreederCloudPro-alternative pages.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Reciprocal inbound-link sweep is still deferred</strong> per the cluster-plan rule that batches Cluster C reciprocal links after all five comparison pages ship. With C1 and C2 now live, the remaining Cluster C pages are C3 (BreedTools), C4 (Breeder&apos;s Assistant), and C5 (ZooEasy). Once C5 lands, the cross-link pass updates <code>/compare</code> (index), <code>/pricing</code>, and the existing <code>/compare/best-X-software</code> pages to point at the five new alternative LPs in a single atomic commit.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Next.</strong> Per the execution sequence: C5 (<code>/compare/zooeasy-alternative</code>) targets a different audience (breed clubs) and should ship before C3/C4 to validate the cross-audience reach of the Conquesting Ads strategy.
    </p>
  </div>
</article>
